The aerogel scaffold porosity, swelling capacity and structural stability can affect their practical use in biomedical applications. For example, controllable swelling capacity and porosity > 90% are desirable to induce adequate diffusion of metabolites and vascularization, avoiding necrotic core in the scaffold due to hypoxia [10–12]. Table 5
                         shows the properties of the LL-CNF and HL-CNF aerogels prepared with different initial CNF concentrations ranging from 1 to 2 wt.% via freeze-drying (Fig. 3
                        ). The lignin content of the initial CNF solid concentration greatly affected the bulk density of the aerogels. The lowest densities of the LL-CNF and HL-CNF aerogels were 0.009 and 0.029 g/cm3, respectively, achieved at 1 wt.% initial CNF concentration. As the bulk density is calculated based on the mass and volume of the aerogel (Eq. (6)). By increasing the initial solid concentration, the mass of the aerogel increased, resulting in increased bulk density. At 2 wt.% concentration, the LL-CNF and HL-CNF aerogels had bulk densities of 0.025 and 0.051 g/cm3, respectively. Furthermore, the difference on density values obtained from the LL-CNF and HL-CNF aerogels at the same initial solid concentration is attributed to the diameter shrinkage during the freezing step prior to freeze drying (Table 5).
